In this figure, the four most tightly bound
electron shells are plotted as a function

76
00:07:18,220 --> 00:07:23,560
of Z, the atomic number from Z = 1 (hydrogen)
to Z = 92 (uranium).

77
00:07:23,560 --> 00:07:31,550
The hard x-ray regime can access all elements
with atomic numbers above Z = 20 (the atomic

78
00:07:31,550 --> 00:07:33,590
number of calcium).

79
00:07:33,590 --> 00:07:40,640
This property can be exploited in hard x-ray
spectroscopies and also in crystallography,

80
00:07:40,640 --> 00:07:45,690
as an aid to solving structures from data
recorded at specially chosen photon energies.

81
00:07:45,690 --> 00:07:51,000
What are then the main attributes of soft
x-rays that make them useful tools in investigating

82
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:53,490
the properties of matter?

83
00:07:53,490 --> 00:07:59,370
The lower photon energy of x-rays means that
they interact primarily with light atoms and

84
00:07:59,370 --> 00:08:03,210
the outer, or valence, electrons of heavier
atoms.

85
00:08:03,210 --> 00:08:10,389
This is exploited to investigate many different
properties of materials such as, for example,

86
00:08:10,389 --> 00:08:17,350
the electronic properties of metals, semiconductors,
and superconductors; the chemical composition

87
00:08:17,350 --> 00:08:27,250
of heterogeneous systems; or the imaging of
magnetic domains down to the nanometer scale.

